WEBVTT

00:01.084 --> 00:03.420
[ Rock music plays ]

00:03.420 --> 00:04.588
Alright.

00:04.588 --> 00:06.423
Sumatra Sunrise,

00:06.423 --> 00:07.466
Harissa Honey,

00:07.466 --> 00:08.717
Turmeric Latte.

00:08.717 --> 00:10.385
I like them all.

00:10.385 --> 00:12.054
They're very soothing.

00:12.054 --> 00:14.097
Like the colors
you'd choose for a psych ward.

00:14.097 --> 00:15.557
Do you want to go back
to the browns then?

00:15.557 --> 00:18.143
I really don't.
Just paint it whatever you want.

00:18.143 --> 00:19.561
It's <i>your</i> apartment.

00:19.561 --> 00:21.063
Yeah,
but this is your room.

00:21.063 --> 00:22.272
You know, you should choose.
It's ‐‐

00:22.272 --> 00:23.774
It's not mine, though.
It's...

00:25.651 --> 00:28.070
Yeah.
Uh, what do you think?

00:28.070 --> 00:30.989
Uh, oh, I think
you should hire a decorator.

00:30.989 --> 00:32.783
And I think we really need to
get to the station.

00:32.783 --> 00:35.827
The next 48 hours
are going to be crazy.

00:35.827 --> 00:36.995
Nice to see you again,
Tamara.

00:36.995 --> 00:38.038
Bye.

00:41.750 --> 00:43.585
[ Water runs ]

00:43.585 --> 00:45.963
Hey, do you think,
um, we're being silly ‐‐

00:45.963 --> 00:48.423
you know, taking this long
to pick a color.
Not at all.

00:48.423 --> 00:50.842
Though I'd argue "we"
is the wrong pronoun to use.

00:50.842 --> 00:53.178
Tamara settled on a color
two weeks ago.

00:53.178 --> 00:55.138
And last week.
And Saturday.

00:55.138 --> 00:56.556
You vetoed them all.

00:56.556 --> 00:58.350
I did not.

00:58.350 --> 01:00.269
I just ‐‐ I just really
want to make sure

01:00.269 --> 01:01.728
that she's thinking
this through.

01:01.728 --> 01:03.647
You know, this is her home now.
It's her safe space.

01:03.647 --> 01:05.315
It needs to be perfect.

01:05.315 --> 01:07.442
Mm.
Oh, hey.
Don't forget your bag.

01:07.442 --> 01:09.069
Yeah.
What the heck is in here?

01:09.069 --> 01:10.571
Books.

01:10.571 --> 01:12.072
Tim gave me a long list
of books to read

01:12.072 --> 01:13.490
to help me become
a training officer.

01:13.490 --> 01:16.577
According to him,
I have to up my Investigative IQ

01:16.577 --> 01:18.620
if I'm gonna make T. O.
in a year.
[ Sighs ]

01:18.620 --> 01:21.415
Is it weird for you that Tim
is officially no longer a T. O.?

01:21.415 --> 01:23.709
No. I mean, I'm moving on
with my career.

01:23.709 --> 01:25.460
And today so is he.

01:25.460 --> 01:27.921
Plus you secretly love it
that technically

01:27.921 --> 01:29.548
he's a rookie sergeant.

01:29.548 --> 01:31.675
Is he?
I hadn't thought of that.

01:35.304 --> 01:39.349
♪ Oh, whoa,
oh, oh, oh, oh, oh ♪

01:39.349 --> 01:44.730
♪ I'm gonna win for you like
I know you want me to do ♪

01:44.730 --> 01:46.565
♪ Hey ♪

01:46.565 --> 01:50.944
So, uh, rumor is
I am getting a new rookie today.

01:50.944 --> 01:52.904
Yeah, we need
to talk about him.

01:52.904 --> 01:54.239
Okay.
That doesn't sound good.

01:54.239 --> 01:55.699
[ Knock on glass ]

01:55.699 --> 01:57.743
You wanted to see me,
sir?
Yeah.

01:57.743 --> 01:59.494
I'm afraid I got a complaint

01:59.494 --> 02:01.079
about your uniform.

02:01.079 --> 02:02.998
Yeah. That Department‐issued
sergeant's badge ‐‐

02:02.998 --> 02:04.458
that won't do.

02:04.458 --> 02:06.168
That is 80% tin.

02:06.168 --> 02:08.670
But this is solid silver
and real gold.

02:08.670 --> 02:10.839
Thank you.

02:10.839 --> 02:13.008
Sgt. Grey:
See, you earned it.

02:13.008 --> 02:14.760
I won't let you down.

02:14.760 --> 02:18.347
Sure you will.
This is a hard transition.

02:18.347 --> 02:20.849
You will fail
as much as you succeed.

02:20.849 --> 02:22.142
And you are
starting your watch

02:22.142 --> 02:23.810
on the craziest weekend
of the year.

02:23.810 --> 02:25.771
I can handle it.
I've been a supervisor before.

02:25.771 --> 02:26.980
Different animal.

02:26.980 --> 02:28.315
T.O.s are drill sergeants.

02:28.315 --> 02:30.442
Supervisors ‐‐ coaches.

02:30.442 --> 02:32.194
Orange slices, got it.

02:32.194 --> 02:34.529
Those stripes are Velcro,
Sergeant.

02:34.529 --> 02:36.448
Yes, sir.

02:36.448 --> 02:37.658
You'll do Roll Call today.

02:37.658 --> 02:40.452
Yes, sir.
I'll go get up to speed.

02:40.452 --> 02:41.536
Thank you.

02:41.536 --> 02:42.746
Good luck.

02:44.081 --> 02:46.208
Oh, uh,
w‐what was my bad news?

02:46.208 --> 02:47.209
Your new rookie

02:47.209 --> 02:48.418
is Aaron Thorsen.

02:48.418 --> 02:49.920
[ Laughs ] Poor thing.

02:49.920 --> 02:50.921
If I had the same name

02:50.921 --> 02:52.172
as a tabloid murderer,

02:52.172 --> 02:53.632
I would definitely change it
immediately.

02:53.632 --> 02:55.884
Especially if I was
joining the LAPD.

02:55.884 --> 02:57.135
Yeah.

02:57.135 --> 02:59.179
But he's <i>the</i> Aaron Thorsen.

02:59.179 --> 03:00.972
And he was exonerated.

03:00.972 --> 03:04.518
Okay. So the LAPD is just
letting anybody in now?

03:04.518 --> 03:06.770
No. Officer Thorsen had to sue

03:06.770 --> 03:08.313
to get into the Academy.

03:08.313 --> 03:10.232
But he earned solid scores
once there.

03:10.232 --> 03:12.484
And now
he is your new rookie.

03:12.484 --> 03:14.986
So, the question is:
Are you going to condemn him

03:14.986 --> 03:16.655
before you meet him,

03:16.655 --> 03:19.032
or give him five minutes
to prove he deserves to be here?

03:19.032 --> 03:21.076
If he can't hack it,
I will cut him.

03:21.076 --> 03:22.077
Lawsuit or no.

03:24.079 --> 03:25.956
[ Sighs heavily ]

03:28.125 --> 03:30.794
Oh, my God.
Do you know who that guy is?

03:30.794 --> 03:32.421
Um...

03:32.421 --> 03:33.422
Oh, that's the new rookie.

03:33.422 --> 03:34.464
We should introduce ourselves.

03:34.464 --> 03:36.049
Oh, no.

03:36.049 --> 03:38.385
Do you honestly
not recognize him?

03:38.385 --> 03:39.803
Is he not
the new rookie?

03:39.803 --> 03:42.389
That's Aaron Thorsen.

03:42.389 --> 03:43.849
Wha‐‐ Rich kid.

03:43.849 --> 03:45.475
TikTok famous
before he got arrested

03:45.475 --> 03:47.102
for murdering
his roommate in Paris

03:47.102 --> 03:48.770
while he was
studying abroad.

03:48.770 --> 03:51.440
Right. Oh, right. God.
That trial went on forever.

03:51.440 --> 03:53.942
<i>Trials</i> plural.
The case was a mess.

03:53.942 --> 03:55.569
The dynamics between
two of the investigators

03:55.569 --> 03:57.028
really drove
a lot of the issues.

03:57.028 --> 03:58.321
How do you know all that?

03:58.321 --> 04:00.115
I taught myself French
so I could follow the coverage.

04:01.575 --> 04:03.368
Of course you did.

04:05.328 --> 04:08.290
Officer Thorsen.
Yes, ma'am.

04:08.290 --> 04:09.875
I am Detective Nyla Harper,

04:09.875 --> 04:11.293
your training officer.

04:11.293 --> 04:12.961
Nice to meet you, ma'am.
I would hold off

04:12.961 --> 04:14.379
on that sentiment.

04:14.379 --> 04:15.380
I'm gonna make this

04:15.380 --> 04:17.215
very hard on you.

04:17.215 --> 04:20.218
You are getting the equivalent
of five minutes today

04:20.218 --> 04:22.012
to prove to me
why your infamy

04:22.012 --> 04:24.347
doesn't make you a liability
to this Department,

04:24.347 --> 04:27.142
and a threat to my safety.
Yes, ma'am.

04:27.142 --> 04:29.519
I will put your past
front and center

04:29.519 --> 04:31.229
because that
is what the public will do

04:31.229 --> 04:32.773
when we are
out on the street.

04:32.773 --> 04:36.193
So you better be squared away,
five minutes.

04:36.193 --> 04:38.487
Or your shift
will be over by lunch.

04:38.487 --> 04:40.071
Yes, ma'am.

04:40.071 --> 04:41.531
Mnh‐mnh‐mnh.

04:41.531 --> 04:43.074
Rookies sit
in the front row.

04:43.074 --> 04:44.618
Find me after.

04:44.618 --> 04:47.120
[ Officers conversing
indistinctly ]

04:50.624 --> 04:51.708
Sgt. Grey: Alright.

04:51.708 --> 04:53.210
As many of you know ‐‐

04:53.210 --> 04:55.504
we have a new sergeant
in the field today.

04:55.504 --> 04:59.049
Everyone,
Sergeant Tim Bradford.

04:59.049 --> 05:01.009
[ Cheers and applause ]

05:01.009 --> 05:03.553
Okay. Okay. Thank you.

05:03.553 --> 05:05.013
First up ‐‐

05:05.013 --> 05:06.681
we've got a new rookie ‐‐

05:06.681 --> 05:08.225
Officer Thorsen.
Stand up.

05:08.225 --> 05:09.601
Now, there's
a traditional introduction

05:09.601 --> 05:11.186
for probationary officers,

05:11.186 --> 05:13.230
but you are anything
but traditional.

05:13.230 --> 05:15.106
So I'm giving you 20 seconds
to introduce yourself

05:15.106 --> 05:16.733
before the rumor mill ramps up.

05:16.733 --> 05:17.734
Go.

05:17.734 --> 05:19.820
[ Clears throat ]

05:22.781 --> 05:25.408
I know there's nothing
that I can say in 20 seconds

05:25.408 --> 05:27.035
that'll change
the way you all view me.

05:27.035 --> 05:28.870
It's my actions
that will define me.

05:28.870 --> 05:30.789
And I promise to always
have your back,

05:30.789 --> 05:34.042
and I will always strive to tip
the scales towards justice...

05:35.919 --> 05:38.004
...because I know what
it's like when they're
tipped the other way.

05:38.004 --> 05:40.423
And I want to make
something very clear ‐‐

05:40.423 --> 05:43.760
Officer Thorsen
was found not guilty.

05:43.760 --> 05:46.221
He survived the Academy.
He earned the right to be here.

05:46.221 --> 05:48.306
Till Harper cuts him.
[ Laughter ]

05:48.306 --> 05:49.891
Sit down.
Alright. Down to business.

05:49.891 --> 05:51.643
This weekend's gonna suck.

05:51.643 --> 05:53.395
We got the Dodgers
in the playoffs,

05:53.395 --> 05:55.021
six different concerts,

05:55.021 --> 05:56.398
a fancy art exhibit opening,

05:56.398 --> 05:58.024
and the Getty Gala
tomorrow night.

05:58.024 --> 05:59.818
Now, every A‐list celebrity
with a pulse

05:59.818 --> 06:02.237
is gonna be there
in all their blinged out glory.

06:02.237 --> 06:04.114
Paparazzi are out
in full force.

06:04.114 --> 06:05.365
And we're getting requests
for additional security

06:05.365 --> 06:07.075
faster than
we can process them.

06:07.075 --> 06:09.703
Now, I've only seen the
potential for this much chaos

06:09.703 --> 06:12.247
one other time in my life,
and that was at an FOB in Iraq.

06:12.247 --> 06:14.249
So...good luck out there.

06:15.542 --> 06:16.918
Dismissed.

06:16.918 --> 06:19.504
♪♪

06:19.504 --> 06:21.715
Sgt. Grey: Were you trying
to get them to quit?

06:21.715 --> 06:24.092
Just keeping it real.

06:25.427 --> 06:27.095
Not enough orange slices?

06:28.847 --> 06:29.890
Let's go.

06:31.850 --> 06:35.353
Hey. What do you think
of wallpaper?
Love it!

06:35.353 --> 06:36.688
Because I'm not qualified
to hang it,

06:36.688 --> 06:38.607
so you'd have to
hire someone else.

06:38.607 --> 06:41.359
Mean.

06:41.359 --> 06:44.779
Lucy, you are the most
insightful person I know,

06:44.779 --> 06:47.073
you have to see
what's going on here ‐‐

06:47.073 --> 06:50.368
Why you can't decide how
to decorate Jackson's room.

06:50.368 --> 06:52.912
Until you make it okay
to move on,

06:52.912 --> 06:54.748
Tamara will never feel
like she belongs there.

06:54.748 --> 06:55.874
[ Engine revving ]

06:55.874 --> 06:57.876
Whoa. Whoa!

06:57.876 --> 06:58.877
She better be in labor.

06:58.877 --> 07:00.462
Control, 7‐Adam‐15,

07:00.462 --> 07:02.797
we have a reckless driver,
doing 70 down Hope.

07:02.797 --> 07:05.050
[ Siren wailing ]
Possible 23‐152.

07:05.050 --> 07:09.137
Plate: Three‐Ocean‐Edward‐
Boy‐Zero‐Five‐Eight.

07:09.137 --> 07:11.014
Dispatch:
<i>Plate comes back clear</i>

07:11.014 --> 07:13.308
<i>and valid out of</i>
<i>Torrance to Acme industries.</i>

07:13.308 --> 07:15.644
Oh, u‐um...

07:15.644 --> 07:17.896
you mind if I practice T. O.'ing
during this traffic stop?

07:17.896 --> 07:20.774
You wanna
"work on your act" with me?

07:20.774 --> 07:22.359
Like I'm
a no‐nothing rookie?

07:22.359 --> 07:23.777
Yeah.
Unless that would bother you?

07:23.777 --> 07:25.612
No. Not at all.

07:25.612 --> 07:26.780
Show me what you got.

07:26.780 --> 07:28.198
[ Mid‐tempo music plays ]

07:28.198 --> 07:29.991
Alright.

07:29.991 --> 07:32.118
How do we approach
a vehicle, Boot?

07:32.118 --> 07:34.996
Boot? Really?
Yeah. Sorry.

07:34.996 --> 07:36.414
As soon as it came out ‐‐
Can we just ‐‐
Work with me.

07:36.414 --> 07:37.666
It sounded harsh even
just coming out of my ‐‐

07:37.666 --> 07:40.418
I feel terrible.
I'm starting again.

07:40.418 --> 07:42.212
How do we approach a vehicle,
Officer Chen?

07:42.212 --> 07:45.173
[ Chuckles ]
Using "Contact‐Cover."

07:45.173 --> 07:47.425
Good work, Officer Chen. You
will take the Cover position.

07:47.425 --> 07:48.760
Copy that.

07:48.760 --> 07:50.178
Hey.
You're doing really great.

07:50.178 --> 07:51.471
Thanks.
[ Chuckles ]

07:53.973 --> 07:55.392
Good morning, Officer.

07:55.392 --> 07:57.102
Morning, ma'am.
You know why we pulled you over?

07:57.102 --> 07:58.603
I was speeding.

07:58.603 --> 07:59.688
70 in a 40 zone.

07:59.688 --> 08:01.398
It would be criminal

08:01.398 --> 08:03.733
to drive this car
at 40 miles an hour.

08:03.733 --> 08:05.402
The rules are the same
for all cars.

08:05.402 --> 08:09.114
No matter
how expensive they are.

08:09.114 --> 08:10.115
Officer Chen,
you're not in position.

08:11.574 --> 08:14.452
Now, may I see your license
and registration, please?

08:14.452 --> 08:16.830
You could run me, but then
it's gonna be this whole thing.

08:16.830 --> 08:20.291
So how about
I just say sorry and go?

08:20.291 --> 08:22.585
License and registration.
Now, please.

08:22.585 --> 08:25.046
[ Bag unzips ]

08:25.046 --> 08:26.297
[ Sighs ]

08:26.297 --> 08:28.883
Promise you won't freak out.

08:28.883 --> 08:30.009
I promise.

08:32.721 --> 08:34.931
Okay, Claire Ivey. Why don't you
step out of the vehicle for me?

08:34.931 --> 08:36.516
So I can be sure
you won't freak out

08:36.516 --> 08:37.851
and drive away
while I run your documents.

08:37.851 --> 08:40.645
Sure thing.

08:40.645 --> 08:42.147
Thank you.

08:46.818 --> 08:49.654
Mmm. I bet he looks
even better out of that uniform.

08:49.654 --> 08:51.990
What's he gonna find
when he runs you?

08:51.990 --> 08:53.324
A white whale.

08:56.286 --> 08:57.704
[ Static hisses ]

08:57.704 --> 08:59.706
Control, patch me
through to 7‐Adam‐100.

08:59.706 --> 09:01.833
The first lesson of
being a good supervisor ‐‐

09:01.833 --> 09:04.669
do not get to
the crime scene first.

09:04.669 --> 09:06.713
Getting to a scene first
can hurt their confidence

09:06.713 --> 09:08.548
and tells them
that you don't trust them.

09:08.548 --> 09:10.508
Yeah ‐‐
Dispatch:
<i>7‐Adam‐100, I have 7‐Adam‐15.</i>

09:10.508 --> 09:12.343
[ Static hisses ]
Patch him through.

09:12.343 --> 09:14.345
Uh, sir, I just pulled over
a driver for speeding,

09:14.345 --> 09:16.014
a Claire Ivey.

09:16.014 --> 09:17.682
She has
no outstanding warrants,

09:17.682 --> 09:20.060
but she is suspected
in a dozen

09:20.060 --> 09:22.645
multimillion dollar thefts
stretching back 20 years

09:22.645 --> 09:23.813
from L. A. to Hong Kong.

09:23.813 --> 09:24.856
The Regency diamond heist.

09:24.856 --> 09:26.191
[ Static hisses ]

09:26.191 --> 09:27.692
Nolan, Claire Ivey
has been a target of

09:27.692 --> 09:29.360
this Department
for over 10 years.

09:29.360 --> 09:32.197
<i>Detective Lopez got close</i>
<i>to catching her in 2016,</i>

09:32.197 --> 09:33.323
but a witness disappeared.

09:33.323 --> 09:35.158
<i>Uh, it can't be a coincidence</i>

09:35.158 --> 09:37.452
that she's in town on the
craziest weekend of the year.

09:37.452 --> 09:38.828
<i>What do you want me to do?</i>

09:38.828 --> 09:40.997
Cite her and let her know
she's officially on our radar.

09:40.997 --> 09:43.208
And, Nolan, impress on her

09:43.208 --> 09:45.585
that she should
get her ass out of town ASAP.

09:45.585 --> 09:50.673
Now is the time that
he tells me to leave town ASAP.

09:50.673 --> 09:51.883
Well, if he does,
you should listen.

09:51.883 --> 09:53.885
So?

09:53.885 --> 09:57.180
Suspected in 40 high‐end
robberies, arrested for none.

09:57.180 --> 09:59.474
I'm impressed.
What brings you to L. A.?

09:59.474 --> 10:01.810
The weather.

10:01.810 --> 10:05.021
Well, I hear it's going to be
even nicer someplace else.

10:05.021 --> 10:07.148
Maybe you should try there
instead.

10:07.148 --> 10:09.442
[ Dramatic music plays ]

10:09.442 --> 10:12.612
So, does that mean
that I'm free to leave?

10:12.612 --> 10:14.322
You have a nice day.

10:14.322 --> 10:15.573
Thank you.

10:15.573 --> 10:19.702
♪♪

10:19.702 --> 10:21.162
What do you think?

10:21.162 --> 10:24.082
[ Vehicle engine starts,
tires squeal ]

10:24.082 --> 10:26.167
I think that I have
a girl crush.

10:28.253 --> 10:29.587
That's fair.

10:29.587 --> 10:32.465
[ Static hisses ]
Control, 7‐Adam‐19.

10:32.465 --> 10:35.802
Show us on a welfare check
at 3312 Bronson.

10:35.802 --> 10:38.304
So, tell me,
Officer Thorsen,

10:38.304 --> 10:41.349
what are you gonna do if this
welfare check recognizes you?

10:41.349 --> 10:44.727
What I already do:
Nothing.

10:44.727 --> 10:47.605
And if she refuses to deal with
you because you're a murderer?

10:47.605 --> 10:51.359
I'm not a murderer, ma'am.
I was found innocent.

10:51.359 --> 10:53.903
Surely you're not naive to the
reality of false accusations.

10:53.903 --> 10:56.739
Especially against people
who look like us.

10:56.739 --> 11:00.160
How I feel personally about
your case is irrelevant here.

11:00.160 --> 11:03.621
My job is to assess your ability
to become a police officer.

11:03.621 --> 11:06.541
If every single call
is about you,

11:06.541 --> 11:09.460
then [chuckles] this is gonna
make it a lot harder to succeed.

11:09.460 --> 11:12.422
[ Doorbell rings ]

11:12.422 --> 11:13.756
Police!

11:13.756 --> 11:15.175
[ Suspenseful music plays ]

11:15.175 --> 11:15.967
Step back.

11:17.927 --> 11:20.096
Radio it in.

11:20.096 --> 11:21.055
[ Clears throat ]
[ Static hisses ]

11:21.055 --> 11:23.850
7‐Adam‐uh‐19,

11:23.850 --> 11:25.685
we have signs of violence
on scene.

11:25.685 --> 11:28.021
Making entry.

11:29.856 --> 11:31.816
[ Door creaks ]

11:31.816 --> 11:36.571
♪♪

11:36.571 --> 11:40.658
[ Sniffs ]

11:40.658 --> 11:42.827
[ Sniffing ]
Yeah. That's gas.

11:42.827 --> 11:44.579
Holster your weapon.

11:44.579 --> 11:46.456
One spark,
this whole house goes up.

11:46.456 --> 11:49.209
[ Static hisses ]
Control,
alert LAFD and SoCal

11:49.209 --> 11:50.460
we got a gas leak
at 3312 Bronson.

11:50.460 --> 11:52.337
Body.

11:52.337 --> 11:59.677
♪♪

11:59.677 --> 12:03.806
[ Coughing,
breathing rapidly ]

12:03.806 --> 12:07.644
[ Soft music plays ]

12:07.644 --> 12:09.562
There's no pulse.

12:09.562 --> 12:12.106
[ Coughs ]

12:12.106 --> 12:14.567
Alright, come on.
Go. Get out of here.

12:14.567 --> 12:16.236
[ Coughing ]

12:16.236 --> 12:17.445
[ Coughs ] Go!

12:17.445 --> 12:18.863
[ Coughing ]

12:18.863 --> 12:20.698
Control, 7‐Adam‐19,

12:20.698 --> 12:24.369
update this event to a 187,
alert Homicide and a supervisor.

12:24.369 --> 12:26.537
[ Inhales sharply,
coughs ]

12:26.537 --> 12:30.083
A murder on your first call
is a bad sign, five minutes.

12:30.083 --> 12:32.043
♪♪

12:35.296 --> 12:38.758
What do we have?
Victim is Michaela Faris,
32 years old.

12:38.758 --> 12:40.969
Celebrity stylist.
Blunt force trauma to the head.

12:40.969 --> 12:42.595
And it looks like
whoever hit her

12:42.595 --> 12:44.597
turned on the gas
to make sure she stayed dead.

12:44.597 --> 12:45.848
Where's your rookie?

12:48.559 --> 12:50.395
Did he puke?

12:50.395 --> 12:52.188
Yeah. But it was more
than just the gore.

12:52.188 --> 12:53.481
You know,
it seems to have

12:53.481 --> 12:55.900
brought back
some uncomfortable memories.

12:55.900 --> 12:58.778
I don't know. It almost feels
like he shouldn't be a cop.

12:58.778 --> 13:00.989
Luckily he has the best
T. O. in the business
to help him through it.

13:00.989 --> 13:02.573
He can say that
now that I've been promoted.

13:02.573 --> 13:04.993
Will you stay focused
on the scene, Sergeant?

13:04.993 --> 13:05.952
[ Siren wailing ]
Yes, sir.

13:05.952 --> 13:07.620
What's next?

13:07.620 --> 13:10.581
Well, we should canvass
while LAFD clears it.

13:10.581 --> 13:12.959
"We"?
You're supervisor on scene.

13:12.959 --> 13:14.502
A coach, not a player.

13:14.502 --> 13:16.379
You should stay here,
coordinate response.

13:16.379 --> 13:18.881
Right. Harper, grab your Boot,
go canvass the neighbors.

13:18.881 --> 13:20.091
Yes, sir.

13:23.594 --> 13:25.013
Harper.
Hey.

13:25.013 --> 13:26.973
You get anything more
on Ivey?

13:26.973 --> 13:29.767
Car envy.
[ Cellphone rings ]

13:29.767 --> 13:30.560
Excuse me. I got ‐‐

13:32.729 --> 13:34.981
Bailey, hey.

13:34.981 --> 13:37.608
John.
Hey. We have a body inside.

13:37.608 --> 13:38.943
Can you get the gas off
from out here

13:38.943 --> 13:40.194
so we can
preserve the crime scene?

13:40.194 --> 13:42.113
Absolutely.
Mike, will you go take a look?

13:43.614 --> 13:45.408
Uh...how are you?

13:45.408 --> 13:47.118
Good. Uh, you?

13:47.118 --> 13:50.329
No. Good. Yeah.
I'm ‐‐ I'm ‐‐ I'm really good.

13:50.329 --> 13:52.415
Uh, I'm ‐‐ I'm Lucy.
We ‐‐

13:52.415 --> 13:55.293
I know. We met at the, um ‐‐
the wedding.

13:55.293 --> 13:57.587
Right.
Yeah. Of course.

13:57.587 --> 14:00.089
I should go help the guys.
They're useless without me.

14:00.089 --> 14:01.716
Right. No. Of course.
Uh, uh, great to see you.

14:01.716 --> 14:03.134
You too.

14:03.134 --> 14:07.430
[ Police radio chatter ]

14:07.430 --> 14:08.639
What happened
with you two?

14:08.639 --> 14:10.558
Oh. Nothing.

14:10.558 --> 14:12.435
Uh, this is the first
I've seen her since the wedding.

14:12.435 --> 14:14.187
I mean, we texted a few times
back and forth

14:14.187 --> 14:15.563
after I got back
from Guatemala ‐‐

14:15.563 --> 14:17.440
but then
there was the funeral.

14:17.440 --> 14:20.068
And really didn't seem the right
time to start something.

14:20.068 --> 14:24.906
So I ‐‐ Once I found my feet,
I just figured she moved on.

14:24.906 --> 14:28.201
Yeah. Well, I'd say
she's still kind of into you.

14:28.201 --> 14:30.203
You should
ask her out again.

14:30.203 --> 14:32.413
Look, I know
I screwed up back there.

14:32.413 --> 14:34.415
It was just
a little overwhelming.

14:34.415 --> 14:36.584
All this time you've been
trying to be a cop,

14:36.584 --> 14:38.002
it never occurred to you

14:38.002 --> 14:40.838
that you might have to
walk into a murder scene?

14:40.838 --> 14:42.381
I thought I was better.

14:42.381 --> 14:43.925
I haven't had an episode
like that in a while.

14:43.925 --> 14:45.510
But this is good.

14:45.510 --> 14:47.220
I found a trigger,
and I'm gonna work through it.

14:47.220 --> 14:49.347
This is not a therapy session,
four minutes.

14:49.347 --> 14:51.224
This is people's lives.

14:51.224 --> 14:53.184
Work through your issues
on your own time.

14:55.603 --> 14:58.189
Narrator: <i>And it was on</i>
<i>that cold Paris night</i>

14:58.189 --> 15:02.068
<i>that Aaron Thorsen's</i>
<i>life changed forever,</i>

15:02.068 --> 15:03.945
<i>accused by French prosecutors</i>

15:03.945 --> 15:06.280
<i>of committing the gruesome</i>
<i>murder of his roommate</i>

15:06.280 --> 15:08.324
<i>and long‐time friend</i>
<i>Patrick ‐‐</i>

15:08.324 --> 15:10.243
Jack is
finally, finally down.

15:10.243 --> 15:12.370
Who knew rocking him to sleep
in this would actually work?

15:12.370 --> 15:13.830
Of course it works.

15:13.830 --> 15:15.456
It's an unwashed hoodie
reeking of the person

15:15.456 --> 15:17.208
he loves most
in the world.
[ Chuckles ]

15:17.208 --> 15:19.502
You know you're gonna
be wearing that every
day from now on, right?

15:19.502 --> 15:21.379
We should try to
get some sleep while we can.

15:21.379 --> 15:23.047
I just need to finish watching
this episode.

15:23.047 --> 15:24.632
[ <i>Dramatic music plays</i> ]

15:24.632 --> 15:27.218
Why are you watching
a docuseries on Aaron Thorsen?

15:27.218 --> 15:29.178
He's Harper's new rookie.

15:29.178 --> 15:30.930
I leave for a month, and they
start letting in French killers.

15:30.930 --> 15:32.932
He's American.
And he was found not guilty.

15:32.932 --> 15:34.225
After he was found guilty.

15:34.225 --> 15:36.060
Yeah.
The defense was a joke.

15:36.060 --> 15:38.020
If I'd have been his lawyer,
wouldn't have gone to trial.

15:38.020 --> 15:41.190
[ Jack crying ]

15:42.900 --> 15:44.485
I got this.
You, get some sleep.

15:46.487 --> 15:50.283
[ Cellphone vibrating ]

15:50.283 --> 15:51.784
Hey.

15:51.784 --> 15:53.578
Hey. It's John and Lucy.
Is this a good time?

15:53.578 --> 15:54.829
Does that
even exist anymore?

15:54.829 --> 15:56.080
How's the baby?

15:56.080 --> 15:57.748
He's great.

15:57.748 --> 15:59.750
A bit of a nightmare.
I haven't slept in two days.

15:59.750 --> 16:01.919
Yikes. Okay.
We'll make this fast.

16:01.919 --> 16:04.589
Uh, you worked a case involving
Claire Ivey a few years ago.

16:04.589 --> 16:06.632
Let me guess,
she's our new captain.

16:06.632 --> 16:09.427
What? No. But she is in town.
We pulled her over this morning.

16:09.427 --> 16:11.179
I've never been so grateful
for maternity leave.

16:11.179 --> 16:13.431
Is she that bad?
She's that good.

16:13.431 --> 16:14.807
Claire will pull
some impossible heist

16:14.807 --> 16:15.850
and leave you
looking like fools.

16:15.850 --> 16:17.268
Just like she did to me.

16:17.268 --> 16:18.895
Okay. Any insights?

16:18.895 --> 16:20.479
She doesn't carry a crew.

16:20.479 --> 16:22.398
Always hires locals
for the job.

16:22.398 --> 16:25.735
Getaway driver, hacker,
muscle, demolitions expert.

16:25.735 --> 16:27.612
Back in the day, I put together
a list of people she likes.

16:27.612 --> 16:29.780
Check that file.
Will do.
Thank you for your help.

16:29.780 --> 16:31.616
A‐And get some sleep.
Thank you.

16:31.616 --> 16:33.242
[ Cellphone beeps ]

16:33.242 --> 16:35.578
Oh, Bailey.

16:35.578 --> 16:37.914
Hey. Ask her out.

16:37.914 --> 16:39.290
I...

16:39.290 --> 16:40.708
Hey.

16:40.708 --> 16:42.835
Um...

16:42.835 --> 16:45.504
She had to pee.
We all good inside?
Yeah.

16:45.504 --> 16:47.340
We turned the gas off ‐‐
the house is venting ‐‐

16:47.340 --> 16:49.175
I'd give 10, 15
before you let anyone in.

16:49.175 --> 16:51.135
Okay. Great. Thank you.
Uh, Bailey.

16:51.135 --> 16:52.887
I think you're great,

16:52.887 --> 16:54.972
and I feel like we didn't
really, uh, get a chance

16:54.972 --> 16:58.601
because of just every‐‐
everything that happened.

16:58.601 --> 17:01.437
And I feel like I would l‐live
the rest of my life

17:01.437 --> 17:03.898
full of regret
if I didn't take every advantage

17:03.898 --> 17:05.900
of the universe apparently
pushing us back together,

17:05.900 --> 17:09.362
a‐and ‐‐ and just see
if you wanted to try again.

17:09.362 --> 17:12.365
You know? Just a date. I'm not
gonna ask you to marry me.

17:12.365 --> 17:14.075
Which, you know,
I don't have to say that.

17:14.075 --> 17:16.160
I'm suddenly nervous.
I'm gonna stop talking.

17:18.162 --> 17:21.540
Well, I can't have you living
with regret for all of eternity.

17:21.540 --> 17:22.708
Let's do it.

17:22.708 --> 17:25.670
Okay.
Uh, how's, um ‐‐

17:25.670 --> 17:28.089
Tonight?
Tonight. Great.

17:28.089 --> 17:29.131
I'll text you.

17:31.384 --> 17:33.594
Tim: Alright. Claire Ivey
doesn't get out of bed

17:33.594 --> 17:35.680
for anything less than
a $5‐million payday.

17:35.680 --> 17:37.557
The problem is: There are
a dozen targets in L. A.

17:37.557 --> 17:39.267
this weekend
that meet that criteria.

17:39.267 --> 17:43.104
Including the Rothko exhibit
at LACMA and the Getty Gala.

17:43.104 --> 17:45.773
Well, that Gala is gonna be
crawling with private security.

17:45.773 --> 17:48.526
You know, the chaos of this
weekend could just be a cover

17:48.526 --> 17:50.903
to hit a traditional target
while we're stretched thin.

17:50.903 --> 17:52.947
Or she could be trying
to hit a private home.

17:52.947 --> 17:54.740
I mean, I used to party with
kids in high school

17:54.740 --> 17:57.952
whose parents had millions in
cash and jewelry in their homes.

17:57.952 --> 18:00.454
The challenge is a part
of the thrill for her.

18:00.454 --> 18:02.123
After all these years,
I'd think Claire would want

18:02.123 --> 18:04.375
something worthy of her skill ‐‐
not just a payday.

18:04.375 --> 18:05.793
Do we know
where she is now?

18:05.793 --> 18:07.461
Yeah.
Hiding in plain sight.

18:07.461 --> 18:09.797
Booked a suite
at a hotel in Century City.

18:09.797 --> 18:11.841
What about her crew?
Did we run that list of
names Lopez gave us?

18:11.841 --> 18:13.426
No, we don't have to.
Head of security for the hotel

18:13.426 --> 18:15.052
is ex‐LAPD.

18:15.052 --> 18:17.388
We managed to I. D. her crew
from the elevator cam.

18:17.388 --> 18:19.849
Sgt. Grey: Jamie Carr.
Evan Rando.

18:19.849 --> 18:22.184
Sadi Ling.
Allan Gibson.

18:22.184 --> 18:25.479
First non‐binary person to hack
the New York Stock Exchange.

18:25.479 --> 18:27.315
Explosives expert ‐‐

18:27.315 --> 18:28.566
Learned the demolitions trade
from her family business

18:28.566 --> 18:30.109
bringing down
condemned buildings.

18:30.109 --> 18:32.403
Now she blows safes.
Gun for hire.

18:32.403 --> 18:34.739
Former British SAS
turned private contractor.

18:34.739 --> 18:36.574
Getaway driver.

18:36.574 --> 18:37.825
Was an up and comer
on the NASCAR circuit

18:37.825 --> 18:39.368
until he failed
a string of drug tests.

18:39.368 --> 18:41.495
What's the game plan,
Sergeant Bradford?

18:41.495 --> 18:42.997
Well, there's no sense
in being covert.

18:42.997 --> 18:44.582
She knows we're onto her.

18:44.582 --> 18:46.250
So I'd put black and whites
on her hotel,

18:46.250 --> 18:47.126
and on every person
in her crew.

18:47.126 --> 18:48.961
Let them see us.

18:48.961 --> 18:50.212
Maybe one of them
will get cold feet,

18:50.212 --> 18:51.547
she'll have to
call it off.

18:51.547 --> 18:53.716
Nolan, Chen,
she's already met you,

18:53.716 --> 18:55.343
so park yourselves
outside her hotel.

18:55.343 --> 18:57.178
Harper,
you want in on this?

18:57.178 --> 18:59.555
Uh, yeah. But Officer Thorsen
isn't ready yet.

18:59.555 --> 19:01.057
I can handle it,
ma'am.

19:01.057 --> 19:02.808
That is my call,
and I say that you can't.

19:02.808 --> 19:05.561
So you will be working the front
desk for the rest of your shift.

19:05.561 --> 19:07.772
I can't prove myself to you
if I'm not with you.

19:07.772 --> 19:10.024
You can't
get me killed either.

19:10.024 --> 19:12.693
Alright.
Let's get back out there.

19:12.693 --> 19:15.363
[ Officers conversing
indistinctly ]

19:15.363 --> 19:17.657
You still looking
for wallpaper?

19:17.657 --> 19:21.369
No. I am trying to figure out
where Claire got the dress

19:21.369 --> 19:23.663
she was wearing
in that surveillance photo.

19:23.663 --> 19:26.415
Found it.
Ugh, it's so expensive.

19:26.415 --> 19:28.250
She's a criminal,
not a role model.

19:28.250 --> 19:30.002
Who says
she can't be both?

19:30.002 --> 19:32.171
She is brilliant,
career‐oriented ‐‐

19:32.171 --> 19:33.172
Evil.

19:33.172 --> 19:35.675
[ Scoffs ] Listen.

19:35.675 --> 19:38.886
Her drive, my morality, we could
solve the world's problems.

19:38.886 --> 19:41.514
Oh, hey! Where are you
taking Bailey tonight?

19:41.514 --> 19:43.891
Oh, um...Earthing.

19:43.891 --> 19:45.393
Ben recommended it,

19:45.393 --> 19:49.438
so if nothing else,
it'll be expensive.

19:49.438 --> 19:50.564
You're nervous.

19:50.564 --> 19:52.483
I know.
I‐I like her.

19:52.483 --> 19:54.652
She's just ‐‐
Oh, there's Claire.

19:54.652 --> 19:57.571
♪♪

19:57.571 --> 19:58.823
[ Groans ]

20:00.908 --> 20:02.993
You know the spa here
is amazing.

20:02.993 --> 20:04.870
You really should try it.

20:04.870 --> 20:08.207
Oh. So while we get a massage,
you'll, what, steal a Monet?

20:08.207 --> 20:10.167
A Monet?

20:10.167 --> 20:13.379
What am I, a teenage girl from
the '80s decorating my room?

20:13.379 --> 20:15.631
But there is a Jeff Koons
at the Broad that would look

20:15.631 --> 20:17.967
phenomenal at my house in Vail,
so [clicks tongue]

20:17.967 --> 20:21.011
I bet.
But you've hit museums before.

20:21.011 --> 20:22.722
You're looking
for something new.

20:22.722 --> 20:24.640
Someone has been
doing their homework.

20:24.640 --> 20:26.225
Yes, I have.
Thank you.

20:26.225 --> 20:28.728
So, if you're not into Monets,
what is it?

20:28.728 --> 20:31.063
You can't honestly think
you're going to stop me.

20:31.063 --> 20:32.648
I mean, I've gone up against

20:32.648 --> 20:35.067
the best law enforcement
agencies in the world.

20:35.067 --> 20:36.444
Well,
if you're so confident,

20:36.444 --> 20:37.611
why don't you just
give us a hint?

20:37.611 --> 20:39.363
I know you love
a challenge.

20:39.363 --> 20:41.490
Okay. Here's your hint:

20:41.490 --> 20:43.200
By the end of the day
tomorrow,

20:43.200 --> 20:44.994
I will be buying
a private island

20:44.994 --> 20:47.455
and you'll be doing paperwork
and feeling sad.

20:47.455 --> 20:48.873
So the heist is tomorrow?

20:48.873 --> 20:51.000
Sure.
Or I'm just messing with you.

20:51.000 --> 20:53.544
Have a lovely evening.

20:53.544 --> 20:55.087
♪♪

20:58.299 --> 21:00.760
Oh, hey.
How was the, uh, front desk?

21:00.760 --> 21:02.553
Great. How was the stakeout?
Do you need something from me?

21:02.553 --> 21:05.055
Yeah. I heard the front desk
was anything but great.

21:05.055 --> 21:07.683
How many people asked
if you were a murderer?

21:07.683 --> 21:09.101
Nine.
Uh‐huh.

21:09.101 --> 21:11.687
And TMZ showed up?
Briefly.

21:11.687 --> 21:13.564
That's a problem,
don't you think?

21:13.564 --> 21:15.524
No. Not for me, ma'am.
I can handle it.

21:17.067 --> 21:18.861
Unless you're gonna cut me
from the program.

21:18.861 --> 21:20.863
No.
I'm not gonna fire you.

21:20.863 --> 21:23.365
No. I don't have to.

21:23.365 --> 21:25.159
'Cause you are
gonna go home tonight,

21:25.159 --> 21:26.994
and you are not
gonna sleep.

21:26.994 --> 21:29.455
'Cause you are gonna keep
thinking about that woman's body

21:29.455 --> 21:32.500
and the panic that you felt
when we found her.

21:32.500 --> 21:35.294
And you will realize that you
are going to feel that panic

21:35.294 --> 21:37.671
every day at this job.

21:37.671 --> 21:41.842
And then you'll come in
early tomorrow ‐‐ and quit.

21:41.842 --> 21:44.178
And if you don't quit,

21:44.178 --> 21:46.680
<i>that</i> is when
I will fire you.

21:46.680 --> 21:48.641
[ Soft music plays ]

21:48.641 --> 21:49.642
That's not fair ‐‐

21:49.642 --> 21:53.604
I am doing you a favor.

21:53.604 --> 21:55.856
There is honor
in resigning.

21:55.856 --> 21:58.275
In realizing that
you are not up for this.

21:58.275 --> 22:01.362
But if you get fired
from this job,

22:01.362 --> 22:02.822
what comes next, hmm?

22:02.822 --> 22:05.825
The embarrassment,
the shame, the ridicule.

22:05.825 --> 22:08.244
And, Officer Thorsen,

22:08.244 --> 22:11.997
haven't you been through enough
ridicule for one lifetime?

22:11.997 --> 22:14.542
[ Breathes deeply ]

22:14.542 --> 22:16.126
Right.

22:17.545 --> 22:21.048
We're getting off track.
These are the facts we know.

22:21.048 --> 22:22.341
Aaron and Patrick
were roommates,

22:22.341 --> 22:23.926
studying abroad in Paris.

22:23.926 --> 22:25.386
Yeah,
but not just roommates.

22:25.386 --> 22:27.096
Friends who had known each other
since childhood.

22:27.096 --> 22:30.224
Right.
But then Patrick brings home

22:30.224 --> 22:31.684
a girl from the club
one night.
Mm‐hmm.

22:31.684 --> 22:33.435
After a few hours,
she leaves.

22:33.435 --> 22:35.479
We know she leaves
because of the security footage

22:35.479 --> 22:36.981
from across the street.

22:36.981 --> 22:38.357
And the next morning,
Aaron wakes up,

22:38.357 --> 22:40.067
goes to the bathroom,
finds Patrick's body

22:40.067 --> 22:41.527
on the tile floor
with his throat cut open.

22:41.527 --> 22:45.155
Or Aaron was the one
who slit Patrick's throat,

22:45.155 --> 22:47.992
after she left.
W‐‐ And then waited till
the next day to call the cops?

22:47.992 --> 22:49.410
No, no, no.
She did it.

22:49.410 --> 22:51.370
Or her jealous boyfriend,

22:51.370 --> 22:52.746
whose whereabouts
were never established.

22:52.746 --> 22:54.248
And Aaron
somehow heard nothing?

22:54.248 --> 22:55.165
He was knocked out
on painkillers.

22:55.165 --> 22:56.458
You saw the texts.

22:56.458 --> 22:58.752
By the end,
Aaron hated Patrick.

22:58.752 --> 23:00.296
No, look.
Texts mean nothing.

23:00.296 --> 23:01.797
They were roommates,
they argued.

23:01.797 --> 23:04.049
The media
was trying to paint Aaron

23:04.049 --> 23:05.676
as some spoiled kid
who committed murder

23:05.676 --> 23:07.595
because he didn't want to
do his share of the chores.

23:07.595 --> 23:11.515
Or because he did them
so badly.

23:11.515 --> 23:14.393
Okay. Loading the dishwasher
can be complicated.

23:14.393 --> 23:17.855
[ Jack crying ]

23:17.855 --> 23:20.232
We are so stupid.

23:20.232 --> 23:22.359
We could've showered.
We could've changed clothes.

23:22.359 --> 23:25.237
We could've slept.
What is wrong with us?

23:28.407 --> 23:29.867
Am I interrupting?

23:29.867 --> 23:31.535
[ Exhales sharply ]
Please, interrupt.

23:31.535 --> 23:33.203
College is so hard.

23:35.581 --> 23:37.082
Um...

23:37.082 --> 23:39.710
I'm ‐‐ I'm sorry.

23:39.710 --> 23:42.463
I've been so picky
about the paint color.

23:42.463 --> 23:43.839
It's stupid.

23:43.839 --> 23:45.466
Whatever, it's cool.

23:45.466 --> 23:48.260
No. It's not.

23:48.260 --> 23:50.638
I think I've just been having,
like, a really hard time,

23:50.638 --> 23:51.680
because...

23:51.680 --> 23:54.266
[ Soft music plays ]

23:54.266 --> 23:56.268
You know,
it makes it real, that...

23:56.268 --> 23:58.604
[ Inhales shakily ]

23:58.604 --> 24:00.522
...that he's never coming home
and...

24:02.483 --> 24:03.776
I'm sorry.

24:03.776 --> 24:04.985
I know.

24:07.571 --> 24:10.407
[ Breathes deeply ]

24:10.407 --> 24:13.369
Every time
I change something,

24:13.369 --> 24:15.746
it just feels like
I'm erasing him.

24:15.746 --> 24:18.123
I want to be happy
that I'm living here...

24:20.417 --> 24:22.836
...but I can't stop feeling
guilty that he's not.

24:22.836 --> 24:25.005
He would want you here.

24:25.005 --> 24:28.676
He would want something good
to come out of this.

24:28.676 --> 24:30.302
This is good.

24:30.302 --> 24:32.262
And he would mock us,
endlessly.

24:32.262 --> 24:35.307
I mean, look at this place.
[ Laughs ]

24:35.307 --> 24:36.934
It's kinda growing on me.

24:36.934 --> 24:39.103
Yeah, like a fungus.

24:41.021 --> 24:44.942
Please. Do whatever you want
in this room.

24:44.942 --> 24:46.318
Whatever I want?

24:46.318 --> 24:47.778
Yes?

24:47.778 --> 24:49.196
[ Laughs ]

24:49.196 --> 24:50.906
[ Sighs ]
I mean, yes. Yes.

24:50.906 --> 24:51.991
Let's think about it.

24:51.991 --> 24:53.075
[ Doorbell rings ]

24:55.995 --> 24:57.997
Hi.
Hi.

24:57.997 --> 24:59.164
Come in.
Thanks.

24:59.164 --> 25:00.791
You look beautiful.

25:00.791 --> 25:04.044
I'd better. My entire closet
is on my bedroom floor.

25:04.044 --> 25:06.380
I spent two hours looking
for the perfect outfit ‐‐

25:06.380 --> 25:08.632
which said interested
but not desperate.

25:08.632 --> 25:10.843
Hot but not too hot.

25:10.843 --> 25:11.885
Mission accomplished.

25:11.885 --> 25:13.595
You look very handsome.

25:13.595 --> 25:16.015
Thank you.
Um, first thing I put on.

25:16.015 --> 25:18.017
God, it must be nice
to be a man.

25:18.017 --> 25:19.518
So where are we going?

25:19.518 --> 25:21.270
A new restaurant
in Silver Lake.

25:21.270 --> 25:23.981
Apparently all their entrées
are made from mung beans.

25:23.981 --> 25:27.317
Cool.
Um...what's a mung bean?

25:27.317 --> 25:30.237
I believe
it's a legume of a sort.

25:30.237 --> 25:31.989
I think ‐‐ Honestly,
I‐I picked it

25:31.989 --> 25:33.407
just so
I would appear hip.

25:33.407 --> 25:35.492
Mm. I've dated hip guys.
It's exhausting.

25:35.492 --> 25:37.661
Oh.
But I'm sure
the place'll be great.

25:37.661 --> 25:39.663
Okay, um...

25:39.663 --> 25:41.040
How about
I give you the option?

25:41.040 --> 25:43.083
Uh, we can go
eat mung beans ‐‐

25:43.083 --> 25:44.752
So delicious.

25:44.752 --> 25:47.796
Or ‐‐ how would you feel
about going on a stakeout?

25:47.796 --> 25:49.673
Oh, hell yeah.

25:49.673 --> 25:52.259
[ "Irresistible" plays ]
Okay. Let's do this.

25:52.259 --> 25:53.385
Yes.

25:53.385 --> 25:55.471
♪ Help myself ♪

25:55.471 --> 25:57.389
♪ Can't take my eyes off you ♪

25:57.389 --> 25:59.349
Oh, finally.
Here we go.

25:59.349 --> 26:01.477
Thank you.
You're allowed to drink
on a stakeout?

26:01.477 --> 26:04.396
Cops have all the fun.
Oh. I'm not on duty.

26:04.396 --> 26:06.065
There's cars waiting
at every exit

26:06.065 --> 26:07.274
to follow her
the second she leaves.

26:07.274 --> 26:08.776
She?
Mm.

26:08.776 --> 26:11.195
Okay.
Over my left shoulder.

26:11.195 --> 26:13.280
Mm‐hmm.
Tall blonde, great dress.

26:13.280 --> 26:15.240
I don't know how
to tell you this.

26:15.240 --> 26:16.325
But that's my sister.

26:16.325 --> 26:17.659
[ Spits ]

26:17.659 --> 26:19.536
I'm ‐‐
[ Laughing ] I'm kidding.

26:19.536 --> 26:20.579
I'm kidding.
[ Coughs ]

26:20.579 --> 26:21.914
Oh, my God, your face.

26:21.914 --> 26:23.290
That was convincing.

26:23.290 --> 26:26.168
Or maybe
you are just too trusting.

26:26.168 --> 26:27.503
<i>♪ Till we hanging at the top ♪</i>

26:27.503 --> 26:30.839
Fancy seeing you here,
Officer Nolan ‐‐

26:30.839 --> 26:32.925
or can I call you John?

26:32.925 --> 26:35.594
What kind of
alleged master thief would I be

26:35.594 --> 26:37.054
if I didn't do my homework?

26:37.054 --> 26:38.514
[ Chuckles ]

26:38.514 --> 26:40.516
He's divorced. One kid.

26:40.516 --> 26:43.936
Moved here two years ago
from Foxburg, Pennsylvania,

26:43.936 --> 26:44.978
to become a cop,
and you have been

26:44.978 --> 26:46.355
in the headlines ever since.

26:46.355 --> 26:48.607
But, you, I‐I don't know.

26:48.607 --> 26:50.901
And you won't.

26:50.901 --> 26:53.070
Who's your friend
in the silky shirt?

26:53.070 --> 26:55.489
He's not one of your crew ‐‐
we've I. D.'d them already.

26:55.489 --> 26:58.575
Unless you need someone even
more specialized for this job.

26:58.575 --> 27:01.453
Perhaps a pilot?
Expert spelunker?

27:01.453 --> 27:03.413
He's a dentist.

27:03.413 --> 27:04.873
Well, it's getting late.

27:04.873 --> 27:06.959
I should get to bed.
It is a busy day tomorrow.

27:06.959 --> 27:08.210
Enjoy those drinks.

27:08.210 --> 27:09.753
See you in the morning.

27:09.753 --> 27:11.547
Probably not.

27:11.547 --> 27:13.048
Really nice to meet you.

27:13.048 --> 27:15.050
<i>♪ Can't help myself ♪</i>

27:15.050 --> 27:16.176
<i>♪ Can't help myself ♪</i>

27:16.176 --> 27:19.304
Well, I guess
that stakeout's over.

27:19.304 --> 27:21.557
Yes. The stakeout's
definitely over.

27:21.557 --> 27:25.102
But that doesn't mean
that the date has to be.

27:25.102 --> 27:27.479
No. It doesn't.

27:27.479 --> 27:29.356
♪ You got that irresistible ♪

27:29.356 --> 27:30.107
♪ Ooh ♪

27:45.414 --> 27:48.208
Is this a sneaking out
full of regret thing,

27:48.208 --> 27:49.835
or a letting me sleep
thing?

27:49.835 --> 27:53.338
Letting you sleep thing.
Oh, well.
In that case, I'm awake.

27:53.338 --> 27:55.716
I know it's early, I have
a capoeira class to teach.

27:55.716 --> 27:57.467
I'd ask to join you, but I don't
think you should see me

27:57.467 --> 27:58.677
fall on my ass
till our second date.

27:58.677 --> 28:00.387
Second?

28:00.387 --> 28:02.347
Technically,
this is date number three.

28:02.347 --> 28:04.766
Oh. Is it too early
to ask for date number four?

28:04.766 --> 28:06.351
Let me get some coffee
in me first.

28:08.604 --> 28:10.439
I'll call you later.
Okay.

28:10.439 --> 28:11.607
Bye.

28:14.860 --> 28:16.445
[ Knock on door ]
You got a minute, sir?

28:16.445 --> 28:19.239
Sure.

28:19.239 --> 28:21.241
Where's your rookie?
Oh. In a perfect world,

28:21.241 --> 28:23.076
he is about to walk in here
and resign.

28:23.076 --> 28:25.495
I want you
to not stop him.

28:25.495 --> 28:27.497
I heard that you asked
for him to be assigned here.

28:27.497 --> 28:29.666
I did. A wise captain
once taught me that

28:29.666 --> 28:32.294
there's value in having rookies
with unique perspectives.

28:32.294 --> 28:34.004
With all due respect, sir,
there is unique,

28:34.004 --> 28:35.881
and then
there's Aaron Thorsen.

28:35.881 --> 28:38.258
Look, you need to ‐‐

28:38.258 --> 28:41.094
Who clearly isn't
walking in here to resign.

28:43.513 --> 28:45.140
Man: Hey, Aaron.
Good morning.

28:46.433 --> 28:47.893
Why are you dressed?

28:47.893 --> 28:49.186
Didn't I tell you
what would happen to you

28:49.186 --> 28:50.729
if you didn't
turn in your papers?

28:50.729 --> 28:52.439
Then cut me.

28:52.439 --> 28:54.441
I know you think I'm just
some privileged train wreck

28:54.441 --> 28:56.485
who sued his way into the
Department to play dress up,

28:56.485 --> 28:58.111
but I'm not.

28:58.111 --> 29:00.489
I'm here
because I have to do this.

29:00.489 --> 29:03.158
Because what happened to me
was so awful,

29:03.158 --> 29:05.786
I need to make sure it
doesn't happen to anyone else.

29:05.786 --> 29:08.789
And if you block my path here,
then I'll go to Long Beach.

29:08.789 --> 29:10.832
And if they bounce me,
then I'll try San Diego.

29:10.832 --> 29:14.086
Then Modesto or Stockton
and Fresno, Bakersfield ‐‐

29:14.086 --> 29:16.254
until someone
gives me a chance.

29:16.254 --> 29:18.382
♪♪

29:18.382 --> 29:20.634
Because I'll do whatever
it takes to be a cop.

29:20.634 --> 29:22.094
[ Groans ]

29:22.094 --> 29:26.014
♪♪

29:26.014 --> 29:28.892
Alright, five minutes.

29:28.892 --> 29:31.603
Go set up our shop.

29:31.603 --> 29:33.480
If you are this committed,
I might as well make sure

29:33.480 --> 29:34.898
that you are well‐trained
before you end up

29:34.898 --> 29:36.692
at a lesser department.

29:36.692 --> 29:37.985
Yes, ma'am.

29:37.985 --> 29:39.569
Thank you.

29:39.569 --> 29:41.571
♪♪

29:41.571 --> 29:43.949
The night shift said you
were at the hotel last night.

29:43.949 --> 29:45.367
Yeah. Bailey and I
had dinner at the bar.

29:45.367 --> 29:46.785
Oh.
Two birds. One stone.

29:46.785 --> 29:48.328
How'd it go?
With Claire? Or Bailey?

29:48.328 --> 29:50.330
Either? Both?

29:50.330 --> 29:52.541
Claire is definitely planning
on robbing something today.

29:52.541 --> 29:54.918
Yeah.
And Bailey is...

29:54.918 --> 29:56.837
[ Laughs ] Nice.

29:56.837 --> 29:58.088
Yeah. No. I know.

29:58.088 --> 30:00.173
[ Cellphone chimes ]

30:00.173 --> 30:02.217
Ah. Speaking of.

30:02.217 --> 30:04.720
"Thank you again
for a fantastic night.

30:04.720 --> 30:07.597
I had a lovely time, but I don't
think this is gonna work.

30:07.597 --> 30:09.474
Sorry."

30:09.474 --> 30:11.101
I don't understand.
Listen.

30:11.101 --> 30:12.811
As someone who has
been broken up with by text,

30:12.811 --> 30:15.313
I feel your pain.

30:15.313 --> 30:18.525
Yeah. Seriously, though,
I mean, we had an amazing night.

30:18.525 --> 30:19.860
I d‐‐ I d‐‐
What the hell?

30:19.860 --> 30:21.319
This is...

30:21.319 --> 30:23.071
I'm gonna call her.
Should I call her?

30:23.071 --> 30:25.615
Tim: <i>7‐Adam‐15, go to Channel</i>
<i>Nine for a status report.</i>

30:25.615 --> 30:27.951
[ Static hisses ]
[ Sighs ]
No sign of Claire yet.

30:27.951 --> 30:30.162
Um, what about
the rest of her team?

30:30.162 --> 30:31.413
They're having brunch
together.

30:31.413 --> 30:33.999
Brunch? You think
they're messing with us?

30:33.999 --> 30:36.251
100%.
And that makes me nervous.

30:36.251 --> 30:38.211
Here she comes.

30:38.211 --> 30:41.173
Oh,
that is so unfortunate.

30:41.173 --> 30:42.841
You know, as a practice,

30:42.841 --> 30:44.342
you should really pay
those tickets promptly.

30:44.342 --> 30:46.219
On the bright side,
it does match.

30:46.219 --> 30:47.929
Cute.

30:47.929 --> 30:49.931
But you don't actually think
that's gonna stop me, right?

30:53.143 --> 30:59.232
Well. It doesn't matter...
who did what.

30:59.232 --> 31:02.027
My backup plans
have backup plans.

31:02.027 --> 31:04.237
[ Engine starts ]

31:04.237 --> 31:05.614
See ya.

31:05.614 --> 31:06.865
[ Engine revving ]

31:06.865 --> 31:08.700
[ Dramatic music plays ]

31:11.870 --> 31:13.914
Sergeant Bradford,
Claire just left the hotel

31:13.914 --> 31:16.500
on a black motorcycle, heading
south down Avenue of the Stars.

31:16.500 --> 31:17.876
I think they're
making their move.

31:17.876 --> 31:19.336
Surveillance teams,
get ready.

31:22.255 --> 31:24.091
[ Brakes hiss ]
I've lost eyes on ‐‐

31:24.091 --> 31:25.801
Somebody get in there.

31:25.801 --> 31:28.553
All units, move in.

31:28.553 --> 31:30.889
[ Tires screech ]

31:30.889 --> 31:34.226
[ Siren wailing ]

31:34.226 --> 31:36.561
Where'd they go?
In the bus.

31:36.561 --> 31:38.563
[ Tires screech ]

31:38.563 --> 31:45.779
♪♪

31:45.779 --> 31:53.245
♪♪

31:53.245 --> 31:55.330
[ Horn honks in distance ]

31:55.330 --> 31:57.124
[ Water dripping ]

32:01.086 --> 32:03.380
♪♪

32:03.380 --> 32:06.341
Control, show us
Code 6 at 3312 Bronson.

32:06.341 --> 32:08.844
A neighbor reports someone
entering our crime scene.

32:08.844 --> 32:10.428
Who are we gonna find
inside?

32:10.428 --> 32:13.056
It's either a burglar
knowing the homeowner is dead,

32:13.056 --> 32:15.475
or the killer came back

32:15.475 --> 32:17.477
to see what the police took
or left behind.

32:17.477 --> 32:20.105
At my scene, there was a
paparazzi climbing the skylight

32:20.105 --> 32:22.065
to get pictures while
the police were still there.

32:22.065 --> 32:30.073
♪♪

32:30.073 --> 32:38.123
♪♪

32:38.123 --> 32:46.089
♪♪

32:46.089 --> 32:47.841
[ Door creaking ]

32:47.841 --> 32:57.726
♪♪

32:57.726 --> 33:07.986
♪♪

33:07.986 --> 33:10.071
[ Clattering in distance ]

33:10.071 --> 33:16.703
♪♪

33:16.703 --> 33:23.043
♪♪

33:23.043 --> 33:25.170
Police!
Show me your hands.

33:25.170 --> 33:27.464
Oh, my God!
Hands up.
Turn around.

33:27.464 --> 33:29.841
Who are you?
What are you doing here?

33:29.841 --> 33:33.011
I'm Leilani. I'm Michaela's
assistant. I need her laptop.

33:33.011 --> 33:35.388
We are T‐minus six hours
to red carpet.

33:35.388 --> 33:37.974
And I have a dozen clients
to dress before the Gala.

33:37.974 --> 33:39.851
A laptop wasn't found
at the house.

33:39.851 --> 33:41.269
I reviewed
the evidence logs last night

33:41.269 --> 33:42.145
while I was working
the front desk.

33:42.145 --> 33:43.563
No.
It has to be here.

33:43.563 --> 33:45.398
She didn't go
anywhere without it.

33:45.398 --> 33:48.276
And if I can't track down
Emma's choker,

33:48.276 --> 33:50.737
I might as well change my name
and go into witness protection.

33:50.737 --> 33:52.697
Wait.

33:52.697 --> 33:54.866
Michaela was coordinating the
jewelry deliveries for the Gala.

33:54.866 --> 33:56.868
Yeah.
[ Chuckles ]

33:56.868 --> 33:58.036
I know what the heist is.

33:58.036 --> 33:59.246
[ Wolf Alice's "Smile" plays ]

33:59.246 --> 34:01.706
Whenever there's
an awards show or gala,

34:01.706 --> 34:04.251
celebrities borrow tens of
millions of dollars worth

34:04.251 --> 34:06.586
of bracelets, earrings,
and necklaces

34:06.586 --> 34:08.922
to bling out their gowns.

34:08.922 --> 34:12.092
They're delivered by
an armored car before the event,

34:12.092 --> 34:14.761
and then picked up again
right afterwards.

34:14.761 --> 34:17.722
Claire must've killed Michaela
to get the delivery schedule.

34:17.722 --> 34:19.808
And if she wants
to maximize the score,

34:19.808 --> 34:23.144
she'll hit the armored car
right at the beginning.

34:23.144 --> 34:25.814
♪ I scope it out,
then I throw myself into it ♪

34:25.814 --> 34:28.316
♪ I ain't ashamed in the fact
that I'm sensitive ♪

34:28.316 --> 34:30.777
♪ I believe that it is
the perfect adjective ♪

34:30.777 --> 34:33.488
♪ I wear my feelings
on my sleeve, I suggested it ♪

34:33.488 --> 34:35.949
♪ It serves me better
than to swallow in a sedative ♪

34:35.949 --> 34:38.243
♪ I am what I am,
and I'm good at it ♪

34:38.243 --> 34:40.036
♪ And you ♪
[ Tires screech ]

34:40.036 --> 34:45.208
♪♪

34:45.208 --> 34:50.338
♪♪

34:50.338 --> 34:52.382
[ Taser fires,
electricity zaps ]

34:52.382 --> 34:55.552
♪♪

34:55.552 --> 34:57.220
[ Shotgun cocks ]
Put it down on the ground.

34:57.220 --> 35:07.230
♪♪

35:07.230 --> 35:09.149
[ Tires screeching ]

35:09.149 --> 35:18.241
♪♪

35:18.241 --> 35:19.743
[ Gun cocks ]

35:19.743 --> 35:24.831
♪♪

35:24.831 --> 35:30.003
♪♪

35:30.003 --> 35:31.588
Claire! Stop!

35:31.588 --> 35:32.631
[ Gunshots ]

35:32.631 --> 35:35.258
Ugh!
[ Groaning ]

35:35.258 --> 35:39.387
♪♪

35:39.387 --> 35:40.889
It's over, Claire.

35:40.889 --> 35:42.557
Throw your gun out
and come on out.

35:42.557 --> 35:44.392
I don't see myself
doing that.

35:44.392 --> 35:46.353
Oh, now,
I never took you for a quitter.

35:46.353 --> 35:48.188
I'm not a quitter.

35:48.188 --> 35:49.731
I'm just not interested
in prison.

35:49.731 --> 35:50.940
See, now, I thought
you would look at that

35:50.940 --> 35:52.942
like your next challenge.

35:52.942 --> 35:56.237
Escaping from prison?
That can't be as hard as
breaking into the Vatican.

35:56.237 --> 35:57.405
You pulled that off
well enough.

35:57.405 --> 35:59.032
Allegedly.

35:59.032 --> 36:01.618
Allegedly. Right.
Allegedly.

36:01.618 --> 36:03.620
So, what's it gonna be?
You coming out?

36:03.620 --> 36:06.706
Alright. Okay.

36:08.333 --> 36:09.626
I'm giving up.

36:09.626 --> 36:11.836
♪♪

36:11.836 --> 36:13.505
[ Groaning ]

36:13.505 --> 36:18.093
♪♪

36:18.093 --> 36:19.636
Keep your hands
where I can see them.

36:21.971 --> 36:23.390
Turn around.
Put them behind your back.

36:26.017 --> 36:27.769
Guess I underestimated you,
huh?

36:27.769 --> 36:30.397
Oh, don't feel too bad.

36:30.397 --> 36:31.523
Everyone does.
[ Handcuffs click ]

36:31.523 --> 36:33.566
Ow!
Sorry.

36:33.566 --> 36:35.485
Okay. Let's go.

36:40.532 --> 36:43.702
What happened today can't
happen again if you expect
to keep those stripes.

36:43.702 --> 36:45.787
I stepped up.
I took charge.

36:45.787 --> 36:48.123
You put yourself
in the center of the action.

36:48.123 --> 36:50.500
It was the best use
of my skills.

36:50.500 --> 36:52.836
It wasn't a tactical move,
Tim.

36:52.836 --> 36:54.254
When push came to shove,

36:54.254 --> 36:56.548
you just didn't trust
anyone else to do it.

36:56.548 --> 36:59.175
Control freaks
don't make good sergeants.

36:59.175 --> 37:02.429
Look, I know you've got
decades more experience ‐‐

37:02.429 --> 37:03.805
Whoa. Hey. Wh‐‐

37:03.805 --> 37:05.181
A decade.

37:05.181 --> 37:07.434
Okay.
But I got my own.

37:07.434 --> 37:10.270
And directing the action
from a distance works for <i>you.</i>

37:10.270 --> 37:12.147
I don't know
if it'll ever work for me.

37:12.147 --> 37:15.024
I need to find my own way
of being a sergeant.

37:15.024 --> 37:16.526
Fair enough.

37:16.526 --> 37:18.194
Anything else?

37:18.194 --> 37:20.238
Yeah.
It's important to give praise.

37:20.238 --> 37:22.657
An attaboy from the boss
goes a long way.

37:22.657 --> 37:24.367
[ Groans ]

37:24.367 --> 37:25.702
It's against my nature...

37:25.702 --> 37:28.371
but I will give it
a shot.

37:28.371 --> 37:30.373
Make sure you
check the shop thoroughly

37:30.373 --> 37:32.083
